## Tools Used

- CIA Triad – foundational model.
- DAD Triad – adversarial counterpart.
- Authenticity & Nonrepudiation – trust and accountability.
- Parkerian Hexad – expanded security model.
- Bell-LaPadula, Biba, Clark-Wilson Models – formal frameworks for confidentiality and integrity.
- Defense-in-Depth – layered security principle.
- ISO/IEC 19249 – international standard for secure design principles.
- Zero Trust & Trust but Verify – modern trust principles.
- Vulnerability, Threat, Risk – foundational risk assessment concepts.

## Findings

- CIA defines security goals; DAD defines threats.
- Security models formalize enforcement of confidentiality and integrity.
- Defense-in-Depth and ISO/IEC 19249 provide layered and standardized approaches.
- Zero Trust and Trust but Verify modernize trust management.
- Vulnerability, threat, and risk clarify the language of security.
- Balance is essential across all principles.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Apply Defense-in-Depth (multi-layered security).
- Implement Zero Trust where feasible.
- Use authenticity and nonrepudiation mechanisms (digital signatures, certificates).
- Protect possession and utility of data (backups, encryption key management).
- Continuously assess vulnerabilities, threats, and risks.

## Conclusion

- Security principles provide a structured foundation for protecting assets.
- CIA/DAD triads define goals and threats.
- Security models (Bell-LaPadula, Biba, Clark-Wilson) enforce confidentiality and integrity.
- Defense-in-Depth and ISO/IEC 19249 strengthen architecture and design.
- Zero Trust and Trust but Verify modernize trust management.
- Vulnerability, threat, and risk define the language of risk assessment.
- Together, these principles underpin modern frameworks, standards, and incident response strategies.
